The complexities and interconnectedness of local and regional ecosystems, as well as the many potential drivers of change (climate, invasive species, trophic downgrading, etc.) (
 Tylianakis 
  et al. 2008
 ; 
 Estes 
  et al. 2011
 ; 
 Craven 
  et al. 2016
 ), obscure the current and future implications of ungulate impacts. Maintaining ecosystem function and ecosystem services requires high species diversity in multiple trophic groups including primary producers, above-ground insect herbivores and soil decomposers (
 Soliveres 
  et al. 2016
 ; 
 van der Plas 
  et al. 2016
 ), organisms that are particularly negatively affected by high ungulate browse pressure (
 Côté 
  et al. 2004
 ).
